07:36.585 --> 07:38.487
How much?

07:38.488 --> 07:40.021
Uh, what is it?

07:40.022 --> 07:42.792
My grandmother's...
your great-grandmother's...

07:42.793 --> 07:44.427
flour sifter.

07:44.428 --> 07:45.627
Okay.

07:45.628 --> 07:46.862
Do you remember her name?

07:46.863 --> 07:48.396
Which side of the family?

07:48.397 --> 07:50.066
- Matthew's.
- Margaret?

07:50.067 --> 07:52.447
That's your dad's first wife's name.

07:52.448 --> 07:53.749
Can't they both be Margaret?

07:53.750 --> 07:55.451
They can, but they're not.

07:55.452 --> 07:58.454
Uh, Tamika.

07:58.455 --> 08:00.855
No. Harriet.

08:00.856 --> 08:02.425
She should have considered Tamika.

08:02.426 --> 08:04.628
This sifter's like 100 years old.

08:05.962 --> 08:08.396
Okay. Let me do some research.

08:08.397 --> 08:11.800
Got to be at least $1 for every year.

08:11.801 --> 08:12.834
Doesn't work that way, Mom.

08:12.835 --> 08:14.637
- We'll see.
- (SCOFFS)

08:14.638 --> 08:16.805
(COMPUTER DINGS)

08:16.806 --> 08:18.823
You got another hit on your bike.

08:19.977 --> 08:21.711
How much?

08:21.712 --> 08:23.379
$185.50.

08:23.380 --> 08:24.613
50 cents?

08:24.614 --> 08:25.480
Yep.

08:25.481 --> 08:27.283
(SIGHS)

08:27.284 --> 08:28.584
What do you think?

08:28.585 --> 08:30.353
It's been over two weeks.

08:30.354 --> 08:32.485
At this point, I don't think
it's going up much.

08:34.024 --> 08:35.977
I think you should take it.

08:44.301 --> 08:45.736
(BRAKE CLICKS)

08:54.344 --> 08:57.082
Just do it, Mom. Say the word.

09:01.417 --> 09:02.632
Sold.

09:04.787 --> 09:06.890
(COMPUTER BEEPS)

09:26.228 --> 09:27.564
Hey.

09:29.913 --> 09:31.303
Hey, Dad.

09:32.448 --> 09:34.348
Takes a little imagination.

09:35.552 --> 09:36.864
I'll say.

09:37.654 --> 09:38.854
But I think it's a better location

09:38.855 --> 09:41.165
than that last placed we looked at.

09:41.857 --> 09:45.695
We could just pay rent here
till a better one comes along.

09:45.696 --> 09:46.793
We?

09:50.100 --> 09:51.833
I can help you with that
for a little while.

09:51.834 --> 09:52.878
You know?

09:54.704 --> 09:57.639
This location doesn't exactly
set one up for success.

09:57.640 --> 09:58.976
(DOOR SLAMS)

10:00.644 --> 10:02.791
It's just temporary, son.

10:12.823 --> 10:14.941
Dad, you're not responsible
for me anymore.

10:15.792 --> 10:17.297
Do you know that?

10:18.761 --> 10:20.198
Yeah, I know that.

10:21.365 --> 10:24.799
I mean, I... I'd love to say yes
to this place

10:24.800 --> 10:26.469
or... or some other place.

10:26.470 --> 10:29.013
I'd love to say,
"Hell, yes, let's do it."

10:29.840 --> 10:31.357
For you, Dad.

10:31.741 --> 10:33.273
I'd love to say that for you.

10:33.977 --> 10:35.778
It's not for me, son.

10:35.779 --> 10:39.081
But I'm not responsible
for you anymore either.

10:39.082 --> 10:40.682
I don't want you to be.

10:40.683 --> 10:43.552
And I think the main reason
I went to work with you,

10:43.553 --> 10:48.990
or for you, was so I could
still, in some way,

10:48.991 --> 10:50.926
try and look after you.

10:50.927 --> 10:52.927
You know?

10:52.928 --> 10:56.565
Like I tried to after Mom left.

10:56.566 --> 10:58.685
But then I started to resent you for it.

10:59.770 --> 11:01.035
I didn't treat you great, which made me

11:01.036 --> 11:02.937
feel like shit for acting that way.

11:04.674 --> 11:06.442
But do I mean,
do I want to be here or...

11:06.443 --> 11:09.919
or some other place 10 or 20
years from now selling tires?

11:10.679 --> 11:14.182
I have no idea. I really don't.

11:14.183 --> 11:16.519
(CHUCKLES) I'm... I have no idea

11:16.520 --> 11:18.106
what I want to do with my life, Dad.

11:19.555 --> 11:23.859
But I really appreciate
you trying, you know?

11:23.860 --> 11:25.137
I really do.

11:27.164 --> 11:28.797
And I want you to hear that.

11:30.766 --> 11:32.890
I know you did the best you could

11:34.438 --> 11:35.896
or you'd have done better.

11:38.975 --> 11:39.968
Okay.

11:58.928 --> 12:00.596
AMANTHA: Why did he want to meet here?

12:00.597 --> 12:01.875
JON STERN: No idea.

12:03.866 --> 12:06.936
He said he wanted to see you.
I asked where.

12:06.937 --> 12:08.803
He said, "What about
the roller skating rink?"

12:08.804 --> 12:11.606
What the hell am I doing here
is the real question.

12:11.607 --> 12:13.276
Maybe you don't need to know that yet.

12:18.715 --> 12:20.785
What in the world?

12:24.020 --> 12:25.160
Have a seat.

12:33.230 --> 12:34.777
Hello, Amantha.

12:36.799 --> 12:38.046
I'm sorry.

12:39.236 --> 12:41.036
I'm really, really sorry.

12:42.238 --> 12:43.706
For what?

12:45.608 --> 12:47.109
For hurting your brother.

12:47.110 --> 12:49.812
You almost killed him, Bobby.

12:49.813 --> 12:51.666
I thought he killed my sister.

12:54.985 --> 12:57.820
That's all I've been told
since I was 12.

12:57.821 --> 12:59.187
And now?

12:59.188 --> 13:01.789
I don't believe anything they say.

13:01.790 --> 13:03.626
Well, good for you.

13:06.295 --> 13:07.763
You shouldn't be able
to do that to somebody

13:07.764 --> 13:09.731
without paying for it.

13:09.732 --> 13:11.124
It's not right.

13:11.701 --> 13:13.100
I know it's not.

13:13.803 --> 13:14.919
Are we done?

13:16.773 --> 13:19.073
(HEAVY BREATHING)

13:19.074 --> 13:21.885
My mother wanted your mother
to have this.

13:23.712 --> 13:25.259
You don't believe in the U.S. mail?

13:35.958 --> 13:37.326
I am not gonna forgive you, Bobby,

13:37.327 --> 13:39.327
for what you did to my brother,

13:39.328 --> 13:40.929
any more than you forgave my brother

13:40.930 --> 13:44.257
for what he didn't do to your sister.

13:45.802 --> 13:47.020
I understand.

13:47.703 --> 13:49.041
Do you now?

13:50.640 --> 13:52.152
I think I actually do.

13:56.519 --> 13:57.481
Thank you.

14:12.261 --> 14:14.196
(LIGHT FOOTSTEPS)

14:19.020 --> 14:20.520
Hi.

14:20.521 --> 14:22.424
Hey, there.

14:31.533 --> 14:34.198
You've created such beauty here.

14:35.938 --> 14:38.465
I mean, it was just a box, wasn't it?

14:39.257 --> 14:41.118
A big box.

14:42.110 --> 14:43.683
How'd it go?

14:44.980 --> 14:49.482
The theory is you, uh,
go over and over it

14:49.483 --> 14:53.673
until you become bored with it.

14:54.493 --> 14:55.856
Not there yet?

14:57.728 --> 14:58.748
No.

14:59.853 --> 15:01.238
I'm proud of you.

15:03.349 --> 15:05.052
Appreciate the pride.

15:05.874 --> 15:07.616
You're tougher than you think, buddy.

15:10.338 --> 15:13.099
(FLOOR SQUEAKS)

15:13.676 --> 15:18.180
And you are (SIGH) not as tough
as you act, lady.

15:18.181 --> 15:19.212
(LAUGHS)

15:19.213 --> 15:21.316
That stays between us.

15:23.919 --> 15:25.288
Um...

15:26.385 --> 15:28.915
I'm not seeing a lot of
packing around here.

15:29.320 --> 15:31.855
I thought I would finish my book first.

15:31.856 --> 15:33.325
Your thousand-page book?

15:33.326 --> 15:34.827
838.

15:34.828 --> 15:36.562
Okay.

15:36.563 --> 15:39.670
I am a better leaver than a packer.

15:46.305 --> 15:47.939
So, what are you taking?

15:47.940 --> 15:49.908
I don't know. (CHUCKLES)

15:49.909 --> 15:52.644
A U-Haul trailer's worth,
dealer's choice.

15:52.645 --> 15:54.947
- Art?
- No, he stays.

15:54.948 --> 15:56.684
(CHUCKLES)

15:58.684 --> 15:59.752
Paintings?

16:00.386 --> 16:02.557
Most of it, I'll leave
for the new occupant.

16:03.589 --> 16:05.965
It's kinda the lofty
tradition around here.

16:06.659 --> 16:08.387
That's why there's so much of it.

16:09.529 --> 16:11.029
Can I just pack one box?

16:11.030 --> 16:13.465
- No, no, no, no.
- Just... Just one item.

16:13.466 --> 16:17.635
One item you would like to see
in your new room in Ohio land.

16:17.636 --> 16:18.904
Not my sister.

16:18.905 --> 16:22.740
That is not an item.
That's a not not person.

16:22.741 --> 16:24.578
(LAUGHS)

16:28.048 --> 16:29.362
No, it stays.

16:35.554 --> 16:36.749
Maybe.

16:38.091 --> 16:40.361
Okay, sure.

16:42.062 --> 16:44.664
It needs to be wrapped.

16:45.964 --> 16:48.468
(PAPER CRINKLES)

16:56.909 --> 16:58.348
Do I have to help you?

16:59.011 --> 17:00.894
Probably at some point.

17:01.381 --> 17:02.587
But not now.

17:03.083 --> 17:04.189
Enjoy your book.

17:08.655 --> 17:11.457
- (CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)
- What's wrong with flour sifters?

17:11.458 --> 17:14.461
Nothing, Mother.
It's just supply and demand.

17:16.429 --> 17:17.628
Hey, honey.

17:17.630 --> 17:22.867
Good Lord. There's so much less.

17:22.867 --> 17:24.135
I sold my bike today.

17:24.136 --> 17:26.105
Well, Jared and I did.

17:26.106 --> 17:27.521
Good for y'all.

17:28.282 --> 17:30.442
Do you want your Legos?

17:30.443 --> 17:31.320
What?

17:32.544 --> 17:34.980
I don't know. Maybe.

17:35.582 --> 17:36.914
Do I have to decide right now?

17:36.915 --> 17:38.549
There's no rush.

17:38.550 --> 17:41.519
I was just gonna take a few
bags to Goodwill tomorrow,

17:41.520 --> 17:43.022
so I was just wondering.

17:43.990 --> 17:46.424
- Goodwill?
- Look, they're too beat up to eBay.

17:46.425 --> 17:47.625
Pretty much the only thing people want

17:47.626 --> 17:49.697
is mint, new, in-box.

17:51.257 --> 17:55.595
First, I don't want anyone
eBaying or Goodwilling my shit.

17:57.737 --> 17:58.909
No problem.

17:59.472 --> 18:01.406
I'm glad you're moving on, Mom.

18:01.407 --> 18:03.015
If that's what's happening here.

18:04.978 --> 18:09.114
Just kinda need a warning of
which Janet I'm gonna get...

18:09.115 --> 18:11.048
the one who's moving on or the one

18:11.049 --> 18:13.152
who's still knee-deep in her shit.

18:13.153 --> 18:15.854
Because it seems I never get
to be a part of the good times.

18:15.855 --> 18:18.456
In fact, I usually get
the Janet that wants me

18:18.457 --> 18:21.527
to get knee-deep in the shit with her.

18:21.528 --> 18:23.162
Hey, you shouldn't
talk to her like that.

18:23.163 --> 18:25.029
It's okay, Jared.

18:25.030 --> 18:26.597
No, it's not okay.

18:26.598 --> 18:27.965
No, I'm glad that you're enjoying

18:27.966 --> 18:30.202
your mother being
present for you, Jared.

18:30.203 --> 18:31.514
Savor it.

18:36.576 --> 18:38.565
Where's my dad's Army jacket?

18:40.078 --> 18:42.164
I put it in the cedar chest.

18:44.983 --> 18:47.226
Did something happen today, honey?

18:48.053 --> 18:49.488
(SIGHS)

18:49.489 --> 18:51.123
Nothing negative,

18:51.124 --> 18:53.192
if that's what you're implying.

18:53.193 --> 18:57.061
In fact, it was
extraordinarily positive.

18:57.062 --> 19:00.598
Bobby Dean personally apologized
to me at the roller skating rink

19:00.599 --> 19:03.255
for nearly killing your oldest son.

19:04.002 --> 19:06.571
He's evidently real
torn up about it, too.

19:06.572 --> 19:08.074
Bless his heart.

19:09.943 --> 19:12.978
Oh, and this is for you

19:12.979 --> 19:16.482
from Judy... Dean.

19:20.953 --> 19:22.522
Happy unburdening.

19:38.427 --> 19:40.003
Come on in.

19:45.565 --> 19:47.045
Hello, Mr. Pickens.

19:49.495 --> 19:51.481
Ms. Person.

19:55.083 --> 19:57.786
Well, here we all are.

19:57.787 --> 20:00.922
Yes, ma'am. Here we all are.

20:00.923 --> 20:02.647
Are you ready to do this?

20:03.600 --> 20:05.891
No, ma'am, but, uh,

20:06.928 --> 20:09.733
I always figured this day was coming.

20:11.233 --> 20:12.902
Maybe I did, too.

20:15.538 --> 20:17.686
Well, let's do it.

20:41.329 --> 20:43.966
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

20:48.838 --> 20:51.241
- (KNOCK ON DOOR)
- Coming.

20:53.108 --> 20:55.211
(GROANS)

21:01.250 --> 21:03.322
You're not Melvin. (CHUCKLES)

21:04.019 --> 21:05.456
No.

21:06.187 --> 21:07.387
Come on in.

21:07.388 --> 21:09.458
Oh, thank you.

21:12.261 --> 21:14.555
Have a look.

21:14.970 --> 21:16.385
Grand palace.

21:20.034 --> 21:21.850
You started back.

21:23.105 --> 21:26.142
Yeah, just, uh, once in a while.

21:29.878 --> 21:32.402
I'll quit again after
everything settles down.

21:32.403 --> 21:33.348
(DEEP BREATH)

21:40.388 --> 21:42.656
Janet came by.

21:42.657 --> 21:43.924
The house?

21:43.925 --> 21:46.126
She was asking about us.

21:46.127 --> 21:47.389
Fishing.

21:48.336 --> 21:49.998
Not surprising, knowing Janet.

21:49.999 --> 21:52.631
I told her that we're getting a divorce.

21:53.761 --> 21:56.200
I couldn't lie. I didn't want to.

21:57.703 --> 21:59.072
I understand.

21:59.073 --> 22:02.076
She says she's not gonna tell
your dad anything

22:02.077 --> 22:04.180
until you're ready.

22:08.502 --> 22:10.106
You want something to drink?

22:11.252 --> 22:12.686
Okay.

22:12.687 --> 22:14.155
Want a Coke?

22:14.156 --> 22:17.017
Or... Or a water. Doesn't matter.

22:17.018 --> 22:18.560
Okay.

22:22.364 --> 22:23.364
(SIGHS)

22:23.365 --> 22:24.499
(WATER FAUCET RUNNING)

22:24.500 --> 22:27.203
Do we... Do we get a lawyer now?

22:30.071 --> 22:31.831
I think we're each supposed to have one.

22:32.741 --> 22:34.910
Oh. Right.

22:37.245 --> 22:38.736
Could get a mediator.

22:40.049 --> 22:42.317
I mean, they're not set up
to be contentious

22:42.318 --> 22:44.136
like lawyers can be.

22:44.843 --> 22:46.381
Just another way to go.

22:48.813 --> 22:50.479
I like that.

22:51.694 --> 22:53.126
Want me to look into it?

22:53.127 --> 22:55.027
Or... Or I can.

22:58.500 --> 22:59.794
Okay.

23:00.589 --> 23:01.888
Why don't you do that?

23:01.889 --> 23:03.791
(CHUCKLES)

23:08.077 --> 23:11.203
Told Dad I didn't want to be
in the tire business anymore.

23:12.175 --> 23:13.555
Oh, really?

23:18.354 --> 23:20.501
How did he react?

23:21.357 --> 23:23.909
You know Dad...
keeps it close to the vest,

23:23.910 --> 23:27.627
but I know he's disappointed.

23:27.628 --> 23:30.390
(CLEARS THROAT)

23:30.768 --> 23:33.771
I basically told him
he wasn't responsible

23:33.772 --> 23:36.607
for my happiness and I wasn't for his.

23:36.608 --> 23:38.606
That took a lot of courage, Teddy.

23:38.607 --> 23:42.211
I don't know. Just needed to be said.

23:42.212 --> 23:43.811
Long time coming.

23:45.481 --> 23:47.241
What do you think you might do?

23:50.853 --> 23:53.488
Go work for the man, I guess...

23:53.489 --> 23:55.757
some man who's not my
father and stepmother.

23:55.758 --> 23:57.759
Let him worry about the big picture.

23:57.760 --> 23:59.371
I don't know for sure yet.

24:00.495 --> 24:04.398
Might take some time off.
Go see my mom, maybe.

24:04.399 --> 24:05.893
Have you talked to her?

24:06.603 --> 24:09.506
Not yet. I probably will.

24:12.242 --> 24:13.709
How 'bout you?

24:13.710 --> 24:15.219
Thought about your future any?

24:16.878 --> 24:20.481
I have. (CHUCKLES)

24:20.482 --> 24:24.506
I believe that, um, that God
wants me to serve people, Teddy.

24:25.722 --> 24:27.289
Okay.

24:27.290 --> 24:30.953
Help people... wash their feet,
so to speak.

24:33.428 --> 24:37.898
I mean, I'm gonna finish
my nursing degree first,

24:37.899 --> 24:41.502
and then I don't know, maybe join

24:41.503 --> 24:44.839
Doctors without Borders
or something like that.

24:44.840 --> 24:47.128
Just try and do some good in the world.

24:48.911 --> 24:50.517
It sounds like you got a plan.

24:51.414 --> 24:53.073
I've been praying on it.

24:53.750 --> 24:56.984
And I believe that God
has given me my answer.

24:56.985 --> 24:58.646
I really do.

24:59.622 --> 25:01.237
That's great, Tawney.

25:02.558 --> 25:04.393
You think I'm daft.

25:04.394 --> 25:08.388
No. Just the opposite.

25:09.898 --> 25:12.459
I can definitely see you
doing something like that.

25:13.069 --> 25:16.993
I can see it so clearly,
I can actually see it.

25:18.374 --> 25:19.756
Thank you, Teddy.

25:20.443 --> 25:21.855
That means a lot.

25:27.015 --> 25:28.549
(SIGHS)

25:28.550 --> 25:30.547
You want to go get some
pizza or something?

25:31.654 --> 25:33.855
I mean, you know, nothing on it.

25:33.856 --> 25:35.456
- Not the pizza but...
- (LAUGHS)

25:35.457 --> 25:38.091
Nothing attached to us
going to get pizza, just...

25:42.632 --> 25:45.579
I'd like to spend some time
with you before it all changes.

25:46.903 --> 25:48.434
I think that'd be all right.

25:49.905 --> 25:52.103
I've got about an hour. Is that okay?

25:53.076 --> 25:54.631
It is okay.

25:58.481 --> 26:01.184
Why wasn't Chris Nelms
interrogated, Sheriff?

26:01.818 --> 26:04.051
Well, once Holden broke...

26:04.052 --> 26:06.339
Broke or was broken?

26:06.340 --> 26:10.476
Once he confessed,
Roland and I felt like...

26:10.477 --> 26:13.179
Roland especially felt like,

26:13.180 --> 26:16.215
"Why muddy the waters?" at that point.

26:16.216 --> 26:18.100
What would have been the mud?

26:18.485 --> 26:20.218
You know, there were a lot of rumors

26:20.219 --> 26:22.455
going around with the kids.

26:22.456 --> 26:24.422
Rumors about...?

26:24.423 --> 26:26.324
Hanna's behavior.

26:26.325 --> 26:27.601
Sexual behavior?

26:28.127 --> 26:29.362
Yes.

26:29.363 --> 26:30.563
That night?

26:30.564 --> 26:32.597
That night, before that night...

26:32.598 --> 26:34.509
just a lot of talk.

26:35.669 --> 26:37.236
Let's focus on that night.

26:37.237 --> 26:40.038
Um, we began questioning

26:40.039 --> 26:42.440
some of the boys about those rumors.

26:42.441 --> 26:44.243
And that was in between

26:44.244 --> 26:46.645
our continued questioning of Holden.

26:46.646 --> 26:49.448
Boys like George Melton and Trey Willis?

26:49.449 --> 26:52.084
Those were two we focused on.

26:52.085 --> 26:54.387
And what were their responses?

26:54.388 --> 26:57.657
Trey straight up denied having had sex

26:57.658 --> 27:01.593
with Hanna or having seen any other boy

27:01.594 --> 27:03.296
have sex with her.

27:04.331 --> 27:05.530
And George?

27:05.531 --> 27:08.301
Basically the same thing at first,

27:08.302 --> 27:13.672
but George seemed more nervous,
less sure of himself.

27:13.673 --> 27:17.142
It was like he was
being evasive somehow.

27:17.143 --> 27:18.443
Did you press him?

27:18.444 --> 27:20.112
Roland did.

27:20.113 --> 27:22.000
Was Foulkes leading the investigation?

27:22.001 --> 27:23.048
Oh, no, no.

27:23.049 --> 27:26.718
Not leading. Uh, Roland would spell me

27:26.719 --> 27:28.987
from time to time with interrogations.

27:28.988 --> 27:34.360
We were a small department,
and it was all hands on deck.

27:34.361 --> 27:38.363
And what happened when Foulkes
pressed George Melton

27:38.364 --> 27:41.602
on the issue of his possible
sexual activity with Hanna?

27:48.208 --> 27:50.676
What is it, Mr. Pickens?

27:50.677 --> 27:51.897
Um...

27:53.145 --> 27:57.083
Roland felt like George was
nervous because of something

27:57.084 --> 28:00.286
that he might have seen
rather than something

28:00.287 --> 28:02.555
- that he might have done.
- Meaning?

28:02.556 --> 28:05.524
He focused his questions more on whether

28:05.525 --> 28:09.728
George had seen Daniel
doing something to Hanna.

28:09.729 --> 28:11.063
Sexually, you mean?

28:11.064 --> 28:13.632
Yeah, and against her will.

28:13.633 --> 28:15.601
Questioned George or led George?

28:15.602 --> 28:18.536
Well, depends on whether you're talking

28:18.537 --> 28:21.474
in the moment or hindsight.

28:21.475 --> 28:23.110
In the moment.

28:25.011 --> 28:28.279
You get so caught up
in things, Ms. Person,

28:28.280 --> 28:32.250
and you get this idea
about what happened.

28:32.251 --> 28:36.589
And it's like you get
a kind of tunnel vision.

28:36.590 --> 28:38.626
Is that what happened to you, sir?

28:40.594 --> 28:42.988
Roland got more of it than me.

28:43.697 --> 28:45.467
But it was contagious.

28:46.033 --> 28:47.433
I won't lie about that.

28:53.806 --> 28:59.111
Anyway, we took that information

28:59.112 --> 29:01.213
back to where we were holding Daniel.

29:02.114 --> 29:03.716
What information?

29:03.717 --> 29:06.518
That we had an eyewitness
that would testify

29:06.519 --> 29:10.622
that he had seen Daniel raping Hanna.

29:10.623 --> 29:12.357
George being that witness?

29:12.358 --> 29:13.593
Yes.

29:15.295 --> 29:17.162
What was Holden's response?

29:17.163 --> 29:19.230
He denied it at first.

29:19.231 --> 29:21.333
In fact, Daniel Holden
said it was the other boys

29:21.334 --> 29:23.134
who had sex with her, didn't he?

29:23.135 --> 29:25.103
Initially, yes.

29:25.104 --> 29:28.407
And then he came around
to seeing things your way?

29:28.408 --> 29:31.477
He came around to what
we believed to be the truth.

29:31.478 --> 29:33.312
How long did that take, Sheriff?

29:33.313 --> 29:36.382
I don't know, uh, 10 hours.

29:36.383 --> 29:40.318
It was getting to be toward late
afternoon at that point.

29:40.319 --> 29:41.786
And George?

29:41.787 --> 29:43.389
Did you question him any further

29:43.390 --> 29:46.124
about his possible
sexual involvement with Hanna?

29:46.125 --> 29:48.861
I mean, given Daniel's assertion
that it was the other boys

29:48.862 --> 29:51.731
and not Daniel himself
who had sex with her that night.

29:53.232 --> 29:56.202
I fully intended to, Ms. Person.

29:57.636 --> 29:58.837
But?

29:58.838 --> 30:01.606
Once Holden had confessed

30:01.607 --> 30:04.677
to murder, to rape,

30:04.678 --> 30:08.680
Roland felt like that we
should just cut George loose,

30:08.681 --> 30:10.548
cut all the kids loose.

30:10.549 --> 30:12.785
But before that?

30:12.786 --> 30:16.522
Before you cut 'em all loose,
before Daniel broke,

30:16.523 --> 30:19.859
did you question Trey
about George's claim

30:19.860 --> 30:22.527
of rape by Holden?

30:22.528 --> 30:24.162
Roland did.

30:24.163 --> 30:25.831
And what was Trey's response?

30:25.832 --> 30:28.534
- Just sat there.
- Sat there?

30:28.535 --> 30:32.203
Finally, he asked Roland
to repeat what George

30:32.204 --> 30:36.475
had said about seeing Daniel rape Hanna.

30:36.476 --> 30:37.910
And Roland did.

30:37.911 --> 30:39.911
And Trey's response?

30:39.912 --> 30:41.647
He just sat there again,

30:41.648 --> 30:44.549
like he was contemplating something.

30:44.550 --> 30:48.586
Then he said he did not see
any sex at all

30:48.587 --> 30:51.657
between Daniel and Hanna,

30:51.658 --> 30:54.829
just them arguing with each other.

30:57.296 --> 31:00.900
Did Roland press Trey
to confirm George's claim

31:00.901 --> 31:02.767
of sexual assault against Holden?

31:02.768 --> 31:04.269
Oh, of course.

31:04.270 --> 31:05.571
It was to our advantage to have,

31:05.572 --> 31:08.674
uh, another eyewitness to that.

31:08.675 --> 31:12.277
We were pretty sure that Trey
had been hanging out with George

31:12.278 --> 31:14.813
most of the night, so we believed that,

31:14.814 --> 31:17.549
uh, he must have seen something, too.

31:17.550 --> 31:21.586
But the harder that Roland pushed Trey,

31:21.587 --> 31:23.589
the more he dug in.

31:23.590 --> 31:25.324
That he hadn't seen a rape.

31:25.325 --> 31:26.592
That's correct.

31:26.593 --> 31:28.760
But at that point, we felt like

31:28.761 --> 31:31.296
he was deceiving us.

31:31.297 --> 31:34.299
- How so?
- The way he acted so surprised

31:34.300 --> 31:37.736
when we told him what George
had said about the rape

31:37.737 --> 31:40.706
and how careful he was becoming

31:40.707 --> 31:43.308
before he would answer something.

31:43.309 --> 31:45.311
Just didn't feel right.

31:45.312 --> 31:48.479
Didn't feel right.

31:48.480 --> 31:53.318
But, Ms. Person, again, at the time,

31:53.319 --> 31:56.689
in the heat of the moment,
we felt like that

31:56.690 --> 31:59.904
he was just protecting a friend.

32:01.228 --> 32:02.527
A friend?

32:02.528 --> 32:04.864
You know, by not ratting on him.

32:06.932 --> 32:08.834
Daniel being the friend?

32:08.835 --> 32:10.661
Daniel being the friend, yes.

32:19.913 --> 32:22.415
Of course I was gonna talk to Chris.

32:22.416 --> 32:25.084
But, uh...

32:25.085 --> 32:26.105
But?

32:29.023 --> 32:30.457
Roger.

32:30.458 --> 32:32.726
Roger? Who's Roger?

32:32.727 --> 32:36.228
Roger Nelms, Chris Nelms' dad.

32:36.229 --> 32:38.832
What's his part in all this, CJ?

32:38.833 --> 32:40.734
Who's to say for sure?

32:40.735 --> 32:42.702
'Cept maybe Roland.

32:42.703 --> 32:45.139
Well, that's not gonna happen.

32:47.775 --> 32:51.210
But first, Roger took his sweet time

32:51.211 --> 32:54.014
bringing Chris down
to the station that day,

32:54.015 --> 32:56.882
but he was a long-time
supporter of Roland,

32:56.883 --> 33:00.120
good friend, so nobody pushed him.

33:00.121 --> 33:01.955
When father and son finally arrived,

33:01.956 --> 33:06.159
Roger said Chris was not
gonna talk to anyone

33:06.160 --> 33:07.827
without a lawyer present.

33:07.828 --> 33:09.328
That didn't raise red flags?

33:09.329 --> 33:11.131
Sure, it did.

33:11.132 --> 33:13.232
But Roger was a lawyer himself.

33:13.233 --> 33:14.834
So what?

33:14.835 --> 33:18.071
Daniel had already mentioned
Chris' name, hadn't he?

33:18.072 --> 33:20.441
Well, he'd mentioned a Chris.

33:22.410 --> 33:25.445
Did Roger Nelms and Roland
have a conversation

33:25.446 --> 33:27.127
at the station that day?

33:27.815 --> 33:29.022
They did.

33:29.983 --> 33:31.751
Do you know the gist of it?

33:31.752 --> 33:33.461
I wasn't privy to it.

33:34.055 --> 33:36.389
- It was held...
- In a back room?

33:36.390 --> 33:38.157
In private.

33:39.460 --> 33:43.028
Do you think Roger Nelms
knew exactly what Chris,

33:43.029 --> 33:45.364
and maybe others, had done to Hanna

33:45.365 --> 33:48.393
before he brought Chris
to the station that day?

33:51.439 --> 33:54.810
I've thought a lot about
that, Carl, lately.

33:57.812 --> 34:01.413
Roger Nelms had big plans
for his son, Chris.

34:01.414 --> 34:05.885
A serious charge like rape
wasn't part of those plans.

34:05.886 --> 34:10.356
And Chris was afraid of his dad, too.

34:10.357 --> 34:14.360
So, could I see a man like Roger Nelms

34:14.362 --> 34:19.165
holding his 16-year-old
son's feet to the fire

34:19.166 --> 34:24.070
till Chris caved and admitted
what he had done?

34:24.071 --> 34:29.208
Now that's more likely to me
than Chris keeping a lie going

34:29.210 --> 34:31.371
under those same conditions.

34:33.045 --> 34:34.675
But now it's just a guess.

34:38.052 --> 34:39.418
Did Foulkes share with you

34:39.420 --> 34:42.855
any part of his conversation
with Roger Nelms?

34:42.856 --> 34:44.224
He did not.

34:44.225 --> 34:45.424
He said, "Let's just hold off

34:45.425 --> 34:47.511
on talking to Chris officially.

34:48.129 --> 34:50.094
Keep him in our back pocket

34:50.096 --> 34:53.998
and wait and see
if Holden would, um ..."

34:54.000 --> 34:55.353
Cave?

34:56.837 --> 34:59.240
In a word, yes.

35:06.314 --> 35:07.848
(TAPE RIPS)

35:16.991 --> 35:18.216
Box.

35:19.459 --> 35:21.328
Box.

35:23.096 --> 35:25.990
Put more things in box.

35:29.437 --> 35:32.905
Physically pick stuff up.

35:32.906 --> 35:35.910
Put it in the box.

35:37.645 --> 35:39.246
Feel overwhelming desire

35:39.247 --> 35:43.583
to dump box on ground and keep reading.

35:43.584 --> 35:45.150
That good, huh?

35:45.151 --> 35:48.255
Yeah, it's, uh...
it's hilarious and sad.

35:48.256 --> 35:49.655
It's right up your alley.

35:49.656 --> 35:52.191
There's this part
that I wanted to read you.

35:52.192 --> 35:53.675
Uh...

35:55.462 --> 35:57.630
I do not have time for this.

35:57.631 --> 35:59.159
What is wrong with me?

36:00.267 --> 36:01.604
You're just afraid.

36:02.636 --> 36:05.237
Why am I going again?

36:05.238 --> 36:09.242
Because you have a job there
with health insurance

36:09.243 --> 36:14.347
and, uh, a sister, a-a mother,

36:14.348 --> 36:16.250
family there for you.

36:18.185 --> 36:21.487
What if I just stayed here?

36:21.488 --> 36:23.255
(SIGHS)

36:23.256 --> 36:24.624
You'd have to unpack.

36:24.625 --> 36:26.693
No, seriously, what if I just

36:26.694 --> 36:29.496
pulled a Chloe on the whole plan,

36:29.497 --> 36:33.199
just stayed here in bohemia?

36:33.200 --> 36:37.202
Run away before I ever went
to where I'm running from.

36:37.203 --> 36:39.072
(SIGHS)

36:39.073 --> 36:41.333
What if, Daniel?

36:43.209 --> 36:46.345
I would love for you to stay, Chloe.

36:46.346 --> 36:47.764
I really would.

36:50.451 --> 36:52.554
I'm mad for you.

36:54.455 --> 36:57.023
You've un-bored me.

36:57.024 --> 37:01.695
You've given me, if not hope,
hope for hope.

37:01.696 --> 37:06.365
You've given me strength, courage.

37:06.366 --> 37:08.856
No. You already had courage.

37:09.569 --> 37:11.529
You wouldn't have made it
this far if you didn't.

37:14.674 --> 37:19.546
And I couldn't even
imagine, in some way,

37:19.547 --> 37:24.316
being a part of that little
miracle thing inside your belly.

37:24.317 --> 37:26.269
You could be the weird uncle.

37:27.687 --> 37:30.562
The good, weird Uncle Dan.

37:31.491 --> 37:35.494
I just want what's best for you, Chloe.

37:35.495 --> 37:37.987
And your baby. And your life.

37:39.133 --> 37:42.369
And I'm not sure that being with me

37:42.370 --> 37:49.041
or being around me
in the long term is...

37:49.042 --> 37:50.122
Is.

37:51.544 --> 37:53.435
I thought you were a romantic.

37:55.750 --> 37:58.868
I'm 19 years and 8 months away

37:59.352 --> 38:02.155
from not having to see
a probation officer

38:02.156 --> 38:03.773
every other week

38:04.225 --> 38:06.693
and take random urine tests

38:06.694 --> 38:10.796
and notify law enforcement
if I move across the street,

38:10.797 --> 38:13.050
let alone to another state.

38:14.401 --> 38:17.037
I'm lucky if I sleep
three hours a night.

38:17.038 --> 38:18.849
That's perfect for a baby.

38:20.241 --> 38:21.608
And I'm a...

38:21.609 --> 38:22.730
You're what?

38:24.412 --> 38:27.280
I'm a warehouseman, Chloe.

38:27.281 --> 38:30.215
I pull orders from shelves all day.

38:30.216 --> 38:33.385
A-And I'm lucky to have that job.

38:33.386 --> 38:37.724
I make $7.85 an hour,
and that's after a raise.

38:37.725 --> 38:42.998
That's $314 a week in the 21st century.

38:45.265 --> 38:48.068
It's not romantic.

38:49.470 --> 38:51.002
It's stark.

38:51.772 --> 38:53.375
It's real.

38:55.810 --> 39:00.205
And I had to get real to
survive in the world.

39:13.593 --> 39:15.974
Do you like Harry Nilsson, Daniel?

39:19.700 --> 39:23.836
I-I-I don't think I know his music.

39:23.837 --> 39:25.402
You're gonna like him.

39:28.609 --> 39:33.579
If I know anything,
I just bet that Daniel Holden

39:33.580 --> 39:36.084
will like Harry Nilsson.

39:37.451 --> 39:41.820
Oh, I gotta pack the records, too.

39:41.821 --> 39:44.425
Definitely taking them.

39:49.529 --> 39:50.896
Jimmy Cliff wrote this,

39:50.897 --> 39:54.768
but I sure do like it
when Harry sings it.

39:58.772 --> 40:01.342
("MANY RIVERS TO CROSS" PLAYS)

40:17.290 --> 40:21.693
♪ Many rivers to cross ♪

40:21.694 --> 40:24.796
Well?

40:24.797 --> 40:26.090
It's, uh...

40:28.768 --> 40:30.225
it's beautiful.

40:31.337 --> 40:32.355
No.

40:33.439 --> 40:35.874
Aren't you gonna ask a girl to dance?

40:35.875 --> 40:41.880
♪ Wandering, I am lost ♪

40:41.881 --> 40:43.715
♪ As I travel along ♪

40:43.716 --> 40:45.854
(CHAIR SLAMS)

40:48.355 --> 40:50.289
♪ The white cliffs of Dover ♪

40:50.290 --> 40:52.729
May I have this dance, Chloe?

40:53.826 --> 40:55.728
Always, Daniel.

40:55.729 --> 41:00.432
♪ Many rivers to cross ♪

41:00.433 --> 41:06.738
♪ And it's only my will ♪

41:06.739 --> 41:11.911
♪ That keeps me alive ♪

41:11.912 --> 41:17.717
♪ Well, I've been licked,
washed up for years ♪

41:17.718 --> 41:19.686
(CHUCKLES)

41:19.687 --> 41:22.924
You're a pretty good dancer there, bud.

41:24.658 --> 41:27.760
My mother would make me dance with her

41:27.761 --> 41:29.796
when I was a teenager.

41:29.797 --> 41:31.489
She would make you?

41:32.765 --> 41:36.417
She felt it was important
for a boy to know how.

41:38.605 --> 41:40.049
For his future.

41:42.009 --> 41:44.003
Well, it's paying off now.

41:45.578 --> 41:48.248
It is. Yes.

41:50.683 --> 41:56.923
♪ My woman left me and
she didn't say why ♪

41:56.924 --> 42:00.827
(SMOOCHES)

42:00.828 --> 42:07.733
♪ Well, I guess I have to try-y-y ♪

42:07.734 --> 42:10.571
(INSTRUMENTAL BREAK)

42:17.477 --> 42:18.677
(LAUGHS)

42:18.678 --> 42:21.348
♪ Sweet thing ♪

42:36.696 --> 42:41.733
♪ Sweet thing ♪

42:41.734 --> 42:48.008
♪ And this loneliness
just won't leave me alone ♪

42:50.511 --> 42:55.650
♪ You know it's such a drag
to be on your own ♪

42:59.346 --> 43:02.622
So, doing some spring cleaning, I see.

43:02.623 --> 43:06.192
I am. How's Gladys?

43:06.193 --> 43:07.058
Who?

43:07.996 --> 43:09.028
Edith.

43:09.029 --> 43:10.129
She's down in Florida.

43:10.130 --> 43:11.656
(TRUCK ENGINE STOPS)

43:11.657 --> 43:12.531
How nice.

43:12.532 --> 43:14.335
(CHUCKLING) Yeah.

43:17.505 --> 43:18.709
Hey.

43:20.108 --> 43:21.408
Hey, Teddy.

43:21.409 --> 43:23.403
Jared said you was on a bit of a tear.

43:24.177 --> 43:27.279
Has to be done every 35
years or so, I guess.

43:27.280 --> 43:28.951
(CHUCKLES)

43:30.211 --> 43:31.605
How are you doing?

43:33.277 --> 43:34.510
I'm doing all right.

43:34.511 --> 43:35.545
That's good.

43:36.446 --> 43:38.996
Tawney said she, uh, told you about...

43:41.185 --> 43:43.168
- about our, um...
- She did.

43:43.587 --> 43:44.838
I'm sorry, Teddy.

43:45.989 --> 43:48.404
Hey, what's with the limp?

43:49.393 --> 43:51.263
Hunting accident.

43:57.567 --> 43:59.249
I need to go and tell Dad.

44:00.038 --> 44:02.673
It's not fair for you
to have to sit on this.

44:02.674 --> 44:03.660
I'm okay.

44:05.042 --> 44:07.502
If somebody else finds out,
though, you know?

44:10.647 --> 44:12.355
I just gotta go on and do it.

44:13.384 --> 44:14.920
Get it over with.

44:16.120 --> 44:18.900
He's in the backyard, mulching.

44:18.901 --> 44:20.841
Do you mind being back there with us?

44:22.774 --> 44:24.151
I think it might help.

44:24.910 --> 44:26.523
If you want me to.

44:27.979 --> 44:29.109
I do.

44:29.948 --> 44:31.101
Okay.

44:40.792 --> 44:42.861
(RUSTLING)

44:43.540 --> 44:45.009
Look who showed up.

44:46.097 --> 44:47.721
Hey, Dad.

44:49.167 --> 44:51.067
Just mulching a little bit.

44:51.068 --> 44:54.237
I see that. Looking good out here.

44:54.238 --> 44:56.174
Not like when you cut trees back.

44:56.175 --> 44:57.942
Don't think time of year
matters with mulch,

44:57.943 --> 45:00.578
though I'm sure some TV guy
would tell me different.

45:00.579 --> 45:02.112
Well, I need to do some of that myself,

45:02.113 --> 45:03.880
now that I think about it.

45:03.881 --> 45:05.949
Well, if I got any left,
you're welcome to it.

45:05.950 --> 45:08.109
I'm sure we got plenty at the house.

45:11.856 --> 45:13.825
So, what brings you by?

45:17.963 --> 45:19.846
I need to tell you something, Dad.

45:22.033 --> 45:23.069
Oh, yeah?

45:23.921 --> 45:25.872
There's no good time to do it, really.

45:28.039 --> 45:30.241
I thought I'd wait until after we got

45:30.242 --> 45:32.979
everything with the
store settled, but...

45:36.180 --> 45:39.549
Anyway, Dad,

45:39.550 --> 45:43.862
see, uh, thing is...

45:46.091 --> 45:49.128
Well, go on and tell me,
if you're gonna tell me.

45:52.775 --> 45:55.166
Me and Tawney, uh, you know,

45:55.167 --> 45:58.002
we've been seeing this
lady therapist off and on.

45:59.104 --> 46:01.746
And it's been helping. It really has.

46:02.274 --> 46:04.554
And she's very good at what she does.

46:04.943 --> 46:06.826
You know, empathetic and stuff.

46:09.347 --> 46:11.282
And I think we've both grown from it.

46:11.800 --> 46:13.896
I know we have, in fact.

46:14.318 --> 46:15.466
But...

46:17.256 --> 46:19.471
it's not gonna work out for us, Dad.

46:21.152 --> 46:24.154
And we gave her
a good try, I tell you that.

46:24.155 --> 46:26.485
I mean, we tried just about
as hard as one can.

46:27.291 --> 46:28.946
And I feel good about that.

46:38.170 --> 46:40.630
(VOICE BREAKING)
But we're getting a divorce, Dad.

46:45.476 --> 46:48.722
We love each other, that'll always be.

46:50.849 --> 46:53.182
And she's still family
far as I'm concerned.

46:57.289 --> 46:58.808
But that's just the way it is.

47:02.260 --> 47:04.330
I kind of figured that was it.

47:06.465 --> 47:10.952
You don't hear a lot
of times about couples

47:11.536 --> 47:15.017
coming back together
after they separate.

47:17.608 --> 47:18.995
I guess you don't.

47:20.644 --> 47:22.750
We love you, of course.

47:23.581 --> 47:24.888
Both of you.

47:27.251 --> 47:29.268
We'll support you the best we can.

47:31.188 --> 47:32.542
I appreciate that, Dad.

47:33.072 --> 47:34.390
And it's probably not a good idea

47:34.391 --> 47:37.328
to be alone too much right now.

47:37.329 --> 47:40.844
So, of course, you can come
over here any time you want.

47:42.800 --> 47:44.825
I mean, if it's all right
with your mother.

47:46.271 --> 47:47.770
Absolutely.

47:49.273 --> 47:51.607
Any time, Teddy. We're counting on it.

47:56.748 --> 48:01.110
I'll heed your advice. Thank you, Dad.

48:08.726 --> 48:10.001
Well.

48:13.465 --> 48:15.031
I'm gonna go get cleaned up.

48:19.704 --> 48:21.145
I meant Janet.

48:34.219 --> 48:36.224
Thank you for saving money
today at Thrifty Town.

48:37.389 --> 48:39.223
Got any trash?

48:39.224 --> 48:40.424
'Bout half full.

48:40.425 --> 48:42.064
I'll take it.

48:46.331 --> 48:47.566
Amantha.

48:50.902 --> 48:53.203
Hi. (CHUCKLES)

48:53.204 --> 48:54.706
Jenny.

48:56.708 --> 48:58.376
Hey.

48:59.376 --> 49:01.946
I'm sorry I missed you
at the McGuires' shindig.

49:01.947 --> 49:05.716
Mm. You missed a blow out.
Capri Suns and a bounce house.

49:05.717 --> 49:07.807
Billy said it was quite the event.

49:08.519 --> 49:11.589
Well, Mr. Billy was right.

49:11.590 --> 49:12.989
Of course, Natalie always did have

49:12.990 --> 49:14.861
the biggest birthday parties
when she was a kid.

49:15.559 --> 49:17.962
And the tradition continues.

49:17.963 --> 49:19.430
That's right.

49:19.431 --> 49:22.400
I forgot about her birthday events.

49:23.601 --> 49:25.736
I would always come home
from those so depressed.

49:25.737 --> 49:27.705
Yeah, or pissed off.

49:27.706 --> 49:28.973
"Mama, why can't I have a juggler

49:28.974 --> 49:30.607
at my birthday party like Natalie does?"

49:30.608 --> 49:32.942
That's right, she had a juggler
that one time.

49:32.943 --> 49:35.745
- Serious B.O., too.
- That was because of the polyester costume.

49:35.746 --> 49:37.513
Polyester and juggling?

49:37.514 --> 49:40.286
- That's a terrible combo.
- (CHUCKLES)

49:47.858 --> 49:49.813
(VOICE BREAKING) I'm so sorry, Jenny.

49:50.594 --> 49:52.228
There's no reason to be sorry, Amantha.

49:53.530 --> 49:55.399
Except for still being so pretty.

49:55.400 --> 49:56.902
(SCOFFS)

49:59.536 --> 50:02.774
I missed you for like a year
after I quit talking to you.

50:04.708 --> 50:06.546
It hurt my feelings, Amantha.

50:07.846 --> 50:09.665
Terribly. I won't say it didn't.

50:10.648 --> 50:14.350
But Mama said you were trying
the best way you knew how

50:14.351 --> 50:15.819
to deal with a terrible tragedy

50:15.820 --> 50:18.721
and for me not to take it personally.

50:18.722 --> 50:20.340
Which eventually, I didn't.

50:22.427 --> 50:23.960
God, I miss your mama.

50:23.961 --> 50:26.430
She's available if you need
some bossing around some time.

50:26.431 --> 50:28.233
(LAUGHS)

50:31.936 --> 50:36.372
So, were you surprised to hear
that I was working at Thrifty Town?

50:36.373 --> 50:38.341
Surprised? I fainted.

50:38.342 --> 50:39.977
(LAUGHS)

50:39.978 --> 50:41.845
Seriously, when I came to,
I asked why I fainted.

50:41.846 --> 50:43.747
When they told me a second
time, I fainted again.

50:43.748 --> 50:45.684
(LAUGHS)

50:56.459 --> 50:57.793
(KNOCKS ON DOOR)

50:57.794 --> 50:59.697
You haven't drowned in there, have you?

51:00.380 --> 51:01.700
TED SR.: Still soaking.

51:03.215 --> 51:04.608
You'll get all wrinkly.

51:05.217 --> 51:06.745
I'm already wrinkly.

51:10.255 --> 51:12.068
Want me to scrub your back?

51:14.127 --> 51:15.335
I don't mind.

51:16.596 --> 51:17.825
I guess.

51:32.344 --> 51:35.267
That's the one area you can't
reach yourself, i'nt it?

51:37.683 --> 51:39.285
Nope.

51:44.590 --> 51:45.742
Feel good?

51:47.021 --> 51:48.565
It does.

51:51.663 --> 51:53.317
I love you, Ted.

51:59.973 --> 52:02.643
I love you, too, Janet.

52:22.194 --> 52:24.697
(CELLPHONE BEEPS)

52:27.132 --> 52:28.710
What you listening to?

52:30.477 --> 52:32.236
Uh, homework.

52:32.237 --> 52:33.800
For your therapy?

52:35.340 --> 52:36.675
Yes.

52:36.676 --> 52:38.411
Well, that's good, Dan.

52:42.114 --> 52:43.716
Well.

52:45.451 --> 52:48.185
What is it?

52:48.186 --> 52:49.630
Got a job.

52:50.590 --> 52:53.725
- (CHUCKLES)
- (LAUGHS)

52:53.726 --> 52:55.459
That's great, Pickle.

52:55.460 --> 52:57.662
Working at a dry cleaner's, surprise.

52:57.663 --> 53:00.955
(BOTH LAUGH)

53:01.801 --> 53:03.468
When do you start?

53:03.469 --> 53:04.669
Monday.

53:04.670 --> 53:06.338
You excited?

53:06.339 --> 53:07.759
A little nervous.

53:08.241 --> 53:09.599
Called my mama, of course.

53:09.914 --> 53:10.895
(CHUCKLES)

53:11.344 --> 53:15.213
She pushing 80, but I'm still
her baby, you know?

53:15.214 --> 53:16.314
Yes.

53:16.315 --> 53:18.216
Lord, she carried on, too.

53:18.217 --> 53:20.276
(CHUCKLES) I bet.

53:21.119 --> 53:23.143
Anyway.

53:24.389 --> 53:26.490
We'll probably have
a little celebration,

53:26.491 --> 53:28.160
just the fellas, nothing fancy.

53:28.161 --> 53:29.363
Meat and three.

53:30.195 --> 53:31.296
Meat and three?

53:31.297 --> 53:32.631
That's where you get one meat

53:32.632 --> 53:34.499
and three vegetables... big around here.

53:34.500 --> 53:37.468
Oh, right. Sounds nice.

53:37.469 --> 53:38.835
Hope you can join us.

53:39.272 --> 53:42.639
I wouldn't miss it, Pickle,
not for anything.

53:51.650 --> 53:53.239
How'd your day go?

53:55.755 --> 53:57.937
I helped a friend pack.

53:58.458 --> 54:00.591
Well, that's a gift.

54:03.395 --> 54:06.243
It was. Sure was.

54:07.029 --> 54:10.702
Okay. Well, um, got group in a few.

54:10.703 --> 54:12.260
I'll be there.

54:30.690 --> 54:35.292
(SIGHS DEEPLY)

54:35.293 --> 54:39.058
Chop wood. Carry water.

54:47.440 --> 54:49.707
(CELLPHONE BEEPS)

54:49.708 --> 54:51.142
(PHONE RECORDING PLAYS)
I'm on the ground now.

54:51.143 --> 54:53.952
And it feels like I'm going to sleep.

54:54.514 --> 54:56.757
DR. MILCH: To sleep?

54:57.349 --> 55:01.519
Someone's cutting off
the blood supply to my brain

55:01.520 --> 55:05.926
and then, uh, darkness.

55:07.759 --> 55:11.657
When I come to, there's, uh...
there's something in my mouth.

55:12.331 --> 55:13.731
Something?

55:13.732 --> 55:17.202
A rag... A dirty washrag.

55:17.203 --> 55:22.874
It tastes of soap
and chlorine and... and me.

55:22.875 --> 55:25.243
What are you experiencing?

55:25.244 --> 55:26.877
My neck.

55:26.878 --> 55:29.714
Pressure on my neck.

55:29.715 --> 55:36.581
Someone has their... their foot
on my neck and on my back.

55:38.491 --> 55:40.541
They're pulling my legs apart.

55:41.893 --> 55:48.200
I can't move. I can't fight.

55:48.201 --> 55:49.498
I can't scream.

